            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>

        <h3>Skippable in-stream ads</h3>
        <p>The most common YouTube ad format. These play before or during a video. Viewers can skip after 5 seconds — and you only pay (at CPV rate) when someone watches at least 30 seconds of your ad (or the full ad if under 30 seconds) or clicks through. The skip mechanic means you only pay for engaged views, and the 5-second window before the skip button appears is your hook moment.</p>

        <h3>Non-skippable in-stream ads</h3>
        <p>These are 15 seconds or less and must be watched before the viewer can continue. You pay per thousand impressions (CPM). Because there's no skip option, non-skippable ads guarantee 100% ad completion for every impression served — making them ideal for messaging that requires the viewer to hear the full offer.</p>

        <h3>Bumper ads</h3>
        <p>Six-second non-skippable ads. Bumpers don't have enough time to tell a story, but they're highly effective for brand recall — especially when layered on top of longer-form campaigns to reinforce a message. Google's own research shows bumper ads increase brand recall by an average of 9 percentage points.</p>

        <h3>In-feed video ads</h3>
        <p>These appear in YouTube search results, the home feed, and the related video sidebar. Rather than interrupting content, in-feed ads look like organic video thumbnails with a small "Ad" label. Viewers choose to click and watch — making these a high-intent format for products that benefit from demonstration.</p>

        <h2 id="targeting">YouTube ad targeting options</h2>
        <p>YouTube Ads leverage Google's full audience intelligence stack. The targeting options are among the most sophisticated in digital advertising:</p>
        <h3>Audience targeting</h3>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Demographics</strong> — age, gender, parental status, household income</li>
          <li><strong>Detailed demographics</strong> — education level, homeownership, marital status</li>
          <li><strong>Affinity audiences</strong> — people with demonstrated long-term interests (e.g. "sports enthusiasts," "cooking enthusiasts")</li>
          <li><strong>In-market audiences</strong> — people actively researching or comparing products in your category</li>
          <li><strong>Custom intent audiences</strong> — built from specific search queries the audience has used on Google</li>
          <li><strong>Customer match</strong> — upload your email list and target existing customers or lookalikes</li>
          <li><strong>Remarketing</strong> — target people who have visited your website, watched your videos, or interacted with your YouTube channel</li>
        </ul>
        <h3>Content targeting</h3>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Keywords</strong> — target videos related to specific search terms</li>
          <li><strong>Topics</strong> — target all videos in a YouTube category</li>
          <li><strong>Placements</strong> — target specific YouTube channels, videos, or websites</li>
        </ul>

        <div class="callout callout-info">
          <div class="callout-label">Custom intent is underused</div>
          <p>Custom intent audiences — built from what people have actually searched on Google — are one of YouTube's most powerful targeting tools. A plumbing business can target everyone who has recently searched "burst pipe repair" or "emergency plumber." This bridges search intent with video reach in a way no other video platform can replicate.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="costs">YouTube Ads costs in 2026</h2>
        <p>YouTube Ad costs vary widely by industry, competition, and format. General benchmarks:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Skippable in-stream CPV</strong>: $0.03 — $0.30 per view (average around $0.10)</li>
          <li><strong>Non-skippable CPM</strong>: $6 — $15 per thousand impressions</li>
          <li><strong>Bumper CPM</strong>: $1 — $8 per thousand impressions</li>
          <li><strong>In-feed CPV</strong>: $0.10 — $0.50 per click (varies by category)</li>
          <li><strong>Masthead</strong>: $300,000 — $2M+ per day (reserved, not auction)</li>
        </ul>
        <p>There is no minimum spend requirement for auction-based YouTube campaigns. You can start testing with $10-20 per day and scale based on performance data.</p>

        <h2 id="best-practices">Best practices for YouTube Ads in 2026</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Hook in the first 5 seconds.</strong> For skippable ads, the 5-second window before skip is available is your entire opportunity to retain a viewer. Open with your most compelling hook — a bold claim, a surprising visual, a direct question — not a logo or brand intro.</li>
          <li><strong>Match creative to funnel stage.</strong> Bumpers for top-of-funnel awareness. Longer skippable ads for consideration. Remarketing ads with specific CTAs for conversion. Don't run one creative for all objectives.</li>
          <li><strong>Layer targeting types.</strong> Combine audience segments with content targeting for maximum precision. Target in-market audiences (people researching your category) who are watching videos on competitor channels.</li>
          <li><strong>Use video action campaigns for direct response.</strong> If your goal is conversions (not just views), use Video Action Campaigns rather than standard in-stream campaigns. They optimise bids for conversions and include call-to-action overlays.</li>
          <li><strong>Test multiple creative variations.</strong> Run at least 3-5 creative variants per campaign. YouTube's systems will favour the best performer, and you'll learn what messaging resonates.</li>
          <li><strong>Exclude irrelevant placements.</strong> Review the placement report regularly. Exclude channels or videos that are generating impressions but no conversions — especially gaming channels, kids content, or topics unrelated to your product.</li>
          <li><strong>Retarget YouTube viewers on other channels.</strong> Create custom audiences from people who watched 25%, 50%, or 75% of your video ads. Retarget these warm audiences on Google Search and Display with direct-response messaging.</li>
        </ol>

        <h2 id="mistakes">Common YouTube Ads mistakes to avoid</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Brand intro at the start of every ad.</strong> Opening with your logo and name before establishing a hook destroys view rates. Get to the value or the hook first — save the brand end card for the last 5 seconds.</li>
          <li><strong>No clear CTA.</strong> YouTube ads without a clear next step ("visit our site," "book a demo," "claim your offer") generate views but no pipeline. Every ad needs a single, specific call to action.</li>
          <li><strong>Ignoring mobile placement.</strong> Over 70% of YouTube watch time is on mobile. Creative designed for a wide desktop screen — small text, cluttered visuals — performs poorly on phone screens. Design mobile-first.</li>
          <li><strong>Broad targeting with no exclusions.</strong> Running ads to "all users in country X" without audience or content refinements wastes budget on completely unqualified viewers. Start narrow and expand.</li>
          <li><strong>Not linking Google Ads to YouTube channel.</strong> Without linking, you can't build remarketing audiences from video viewers, track channel actions, or access YouTube analytics within Google Ads. Always link both.</li>
        </ul>

